We have proposed MemMAP a meta-model approach to predicting memory accesses, a central aspect of prefetchers, necessary to improve memory performance. We addressed the impracticality of current deep learning models in prefetching due to their high storage requirement. We improved upon the state-of-the-art, which although does provide compact LSTM models, it requires one model for each application. Such an approach does not scale to large number of applications. It also does not generalize to applications not seen before. We propose to use a clustering based meta-learning approach, where the applications are first clustered and then a meta-model is trained for each cluster. While, it is possible to train one model for all applications, the accuracy was typically lower. Our approach exploits the trade-offs between total model size, accuracy, and retraining steps. We showed that three models (with \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
